05695nam a22006495i 9780774857079DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20071986xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748570797 a10.59962/97807748570792doi  a(DE-B1597)662268  a(OCoLC)748214674  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHN110.V36bV36 1986eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a971.1/3300aVancouver Past :bEssays in Social History /ced. by Robert A. J. McDonald. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©1986  a1 online resource (327 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tCottages and Castles for Vancouver Home-Seekers -- tWorking Glass Vancouver, 1886–1914: Urbanism and Class in British Columbia* -- tSam Kee: A Chinese Business in Early Vancouver* -- tNeighbourhood and Community in Interwar Vancouver: Residential Differentiation and Civic Voting Behaviour -- tThe Confinement of Women: Childbirth and Hospitalization in Vancouver, 1919–1939* -- tThe Triumph of “Formalism”: Elementary Schooling in Vancouver from the 1920s to the 1960s* -- tThe Incidence of Grime in Vancouver During the Great Depression* -- tThe Mothers’ Council of Vancouver: Holding the Fort for the Unemployed, 1935–1938 -- t“A Palace for the Public”: Housing Reform and the 1946 Occupation of the Old Hotel Vancouver* -- tA Half Century of Writing on Vancouver’s History* -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFocusing on Vancouver's social history, the essays written for this special edition of BC Studies treat hitherto neglected areas of the city's past and bring new insights into how its residents lived and worked. Receiving particular attention is the socio-economic and residential structure of Vancouver with one author arguing that the city's economy created an urban working class which was at once more complex and politically more conservative than that of the highly polarized communities on Vancouver Island and in the Interior. An article exploring the pre-1916 activities of the Sam Kee Company, one of the wealthiest merchant firms in Chinatown, offers a fascinating look inside the immigrant world and attests to the importance of business in facilitating immigrant settlement in the New World. Almost forgotten now are the accomplishments of the Mothers' Council of Vancouver -- a group of politically active women who gave support to the unemployed and the strikers from 1935-1938. Another writer recalls the 1946 occupation of the old Hotel Vancouver when a group of veterans protested against the city's acute housing shortage. Other essays deal with elementary schooling from the 1920's to the 1960's, labour history, the geographic and social development of neighbourhoods, crime during the Great Depression, and childbirth and hospitalization. The volume provides a lively portrait of city life over a sixty-year period and lays the groudwork for future analysis of the modern metropolis as we know it today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aBarman, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoldsworth, Derygk W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoward, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDonald, Robert A. J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcdonald, Robert A. J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcpherson, Kathryn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoy, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrong-Boag, V